 2.1 Basic Ethernet
Ethernet is the standard for wired networking in most environments.

Uses MAC addresses for network device identification.

Operates on Layer 2 (Data Link) and Layer 1 (Physical) of the OSI model.

Ethernet frames contain Source MAC, Destination MAC, Data, and an FCS (Frame Check Sequence) for error detection.

2.2 Copper Cables
Twisted Pair Cables (UTP/STP): The most common Ethernet cables.

Shielded Twisted Pair (STP): Helps reduce electromagnetic interference (EMI).

Categories: Cat5e, Cat6, Cat6a, Cat7, and Cat8—each supporting different speeds and distances.

Coaxial Cable: Used for broadband internet and cable TV.

2.3 Fiber Optic Cables
Uses light signals instead of electrical signals.

Faster and supports longer distances than copper cables.

Single-mode fiber (SMF): Used for long-distance communication.

Multi-mode fiber (MMF): Used for shorter distances within buildings.

2.4 Wiring Install
Understanding TIA/EIA standards for network cable installation.

Straight-through cables connect different types of devices (e.g., PC to switch).

Crossover cables connect similar devices (e.g., switch to switch).

Punch-down blocks used for structured cabling in network rooms.

2.4.1 Wiring Install Addendum
Proper labeling and documentation are essential in professional network installations.

Importance of cable management for airflow, organization, and troubleshooting.

Compliance with BICSI and ANSI/TIA standards.

Importance of redundancy and cable testing before deployment.

2.6 Cable Troubleshooting
Common Issues:

Open and short circuits

Crosstalk and EMI

Attenuation (signal loss over distance)

Troubleshooting Tools:

Cable testers: Verify continuity and correct wiring.
